  "prompt": "What has the Supreme Court got by favouring the foreign NGO's in jallikattu case? Don't the judges realise that they have killed Indian culture?",
  "response": "The Supreme Court's decisions are based on interpretations of the law and the Constitution, not on favoring any particular group, including foreign NGOs. In the case of Jallikattu, the Court has had to balance animal rights under the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act with cultural practices. \n\nJallikattu, a traditional bull-taming event in Tamil Nadu, has sparked significant controversy regarding the treatment of animals involved in the event. Animal rights organizations argue that Jallikattu involves cruelty to animals, while proponents of the tradition argue that it is an integral part of Tamil culture and heritage.\n\nThe Court doesn't inherently support or oppose cultural practices; its rulings reflect legal and constitutional principles. Criticism from part of the population is inevitable in any decision, especially in cases where cultural practices are scrutinized under contemporary legal standards.\n\nRegardless of individual opinions, the judiciary is tasked with interpreting the law. Changes to cultural practices typically come from legislative amendments or shifts in public sentiment.",
